# Research Paper: Improving Reliability of Real-Time RTP Audio Streaming Under Packet Loss

## Overview

This repository contains the IEEE-style research paper and LaTeX source for:

**"Improving Reliability of Real-Time RTP Audio Streaming Under Packet Loss Using FEC, Adaptive Jitter Buffering, and Waveform-Substitution Packet Loss Concealment (PLC)"**

The paper presents the design, implementation, and evaluation of techniques that improve the reliability of RTP-based real-time audio streaming over unreliable networks.

---

## Abstract

Real-time audio streaming over UDP is widely used because it provides low latency but does not guarantee reliable packet delivery. Packet loss can introduce audible glitches and interruptions during playback.

This research enhances an existing C++ RTP audio streaming system by integrating:

- XOR-based Forward Error Correction (FEC)
- Adaptive Jitter Buffering
- Waveform-Substitution Packet Loss Concealment (PLC)

The improved system was evaluated under multiple packet-loss conditions (0%, 1%, 5%, 10%, 20%, and 50%), demonstrating improved playback continuity and reduced audible degradation, especially at low and moderate packet-loss rates.

---

## Key Contributions

- RTP-based real-time audio streaming
- FLAC compression for audio transmission
- XOR-based Forward Error Correction (FEC)
- Adaptive Jitter Buffer implementation
- Packet Loss Concealment (PLC)
- Performance evaluation under simulated packet loss
- IEEE-format research paper written in LaTeX

